WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:25.440
Senator Keephover, face the nation.

00:25.440 --> 00:29.360
As the Senate Committee conduct hearings on the cost of wonder drugs, you're about to

00:29.360 --> 00:33.760
see the chairman of that committee, the former Democratic candidate for Vice President,

00:33.760 --> 00:36.840
Senator Estes Keephover, face the nation.

00:36.840 --> 00:41.120
In a spontaneous and unrehearsed interview with veteran correspondents from the nation's

00:41.120 --> 00:46.760
press, Robert Roth of the Philadelphia Bulletin, Charles Von Fremde of CDS News, and Warren

00:46.760 --> 00:49.360
Duffy of United Press International.

00:49.360 --> 00:54.640
And now here is the moderator of face the nation, CDS News correspondent Stuart Novens.

00:54.640 --> 00:59.360
Governor Nelson Rockefeller's withdrawal from the Republican presidential race is generally

00:59.360 --> 01:03.920
taken as meaning that Vice President Nixon will be uncontested at the GOP convention and

01:03.920 --> 01:07.960
that he will emerge as the Republican nominee.

01:07.960 --> 01:12.400
This puts into even sharper focus than before the situation among the Democrats where there

01:12.400 --> 01:15.320
is no clear cut front runner.

01:15.320 --> 01:21.360
Senator Estes Keephover, who was the Vice Presidential nominee in 1956, or the Democratic Party,

01:21.360 --> 01:26.160
may have some views on that situation and he's here now to face the nation.

01:26.160 --> 01:30.720
Senator, apart from party politics, your investigation at the drug industry and major professional

01:30.720 --> 01:34.680
sports and the fact that Congress will be coming back in about 10 days or also matters

01:34.680 --> 01:36.360
that we'd like to discuss.

01:36.360 --> 01:39.040
So if you would, let's take this first question from Mr. Duffy.

01:39.040 --> 01:43.640
Well, Senator Duffy, what's wrong with Governor Rockefeller first is the one thing that

01:43.640 --> 01:48.520
everybody is talking about here in Washington, I think, probably everywhere else in the country.

01:48.520 --> 01:53.600
In your opinion, you feel this is going to make it easier or harder for the Democrats

01:53.600 --> 01:55.600
to elect the President in 1960.

01:55.600 --> 02:01.960
Mr. Duffy, I think it will make it easier and I think that his withdrawal will cause

02:01.960 --> 02:05.560
the Democrats to fight harder to win the campaign.

02:05.560 --> 02:09.680
I think it's unfortunate from the viewpoint of the public interest and from the Republican

02:09.680 --> 02:15.840
party that the rank and file Republicans are not having a contest, not to be able to

02:15.840 --> 02:22.240
decide whether they like Rockefeller better or Nixon better.

02:22.240 --> 02:28.300
There won't be any discussion of a foreign policy and high interest rates in the Republican

02:28.300 --> 02:29.300
ranks.

02:29.300 --> 02:34.520
It shows that the oligarch Republicans are in complete control and Rockefeller apparently

02:34.520 --> 02:36.280
decided he didn't have a chance.

02:36.280 --> 02:39.320
Of course, that's not true of us Democrats.

02:39.320 --> 02:42.360
We have a lot of fine people who are candidates.

02:42.360 --> 02:48.200
Let me make it very clear that I have no national plans whatsoever and I'm not planning

02:48.200 --> 02:49.200
to be one.

02:49.200 --> 02:55.520
Senator Keifal, are our parties wide open and we do have some fine people and they'll be

02:55.520 --> 02:56.760
running in the prime areas.

02:56.760 --> 03:00.880
I think it would have been fine if Nixon, Mr. Nixon and Governor Rockefeller had run

03:00.880 --> 03:05.200
in some of the prime areas to give the people a chance.

03:05.200 --> 03:07.200
That's what we lead in this country.

03:07.200 --> 03:12.000
Senator Keifal, have you indicated indirectly anyhow that you think that Nixon will be

03:12.000 --> 03:15.320
easier to beat than Rockefeller?

03:15.320 --> 03:19.600
Of course, public opinion polls ever since 1948 had been somewhat suspect but nevertheless

03:19.600 --> 03:24.680
they do show Nixon running ahead of any of the Democratic possibilities.

03:24.680 --> 03:28.640
I wonder why you figure that Nixon can be beaten?

03:28.640 --> 03:32.520
Well, of course we have so many Democratic possibilities.

03:32.520 --> 03:38.600
Our public opinion expressions are spread among several candidates whereas in the case

03:38.600 --> 03:43.000
of Nixon, it's just been between him and Rockefeller.

03:43.000 --> 03:48.240
Then furthermore, this is a very dangerous time when one person may decide whether we're

03:48.240 --> 03:57.680
going to have an atomic war or not and I think his time goes on that a lot of people

03:57.680 --> 04:00.680
wouldn't want to place that confidence in Mr. Nixon.

04:00.680 --> 04:05.880
I think it's a nice fellow personally but I want to Democrat to be present with the United

04:05.880 --> 04:06.880
States.

04:06.880 --> 04:13.000
Senator, it's been said by many Democrats perhaps you agree that if Nixon is the candidate,

04:13.000 --> 04:17.920
the Democratic Party will be more united than it would be against any other candidate.

04:17.920 --> 04:20.080
Do you think that that's so?

04:20.080 --> 04:21.160
I think so, Mr. Roth.

04:21.160 --> 04:30.440
I think he's taken a very strong position against the Democratic Party from time to time.

04:30.440 --> 04:33.680
Whereas Rockefeller was considered more of a liberal.

04:33.680 --> 04:40.560
I think the independent voters and the liberals will unite in the Democratic Party more so

04:40.560 --> 04:43.800
against Nixon than what against Rockefeller.

04:43.800 --> 04:46.160
Well, it's clear enough why you're organizing.

04:46.160 --> 04:51.240
I don't want to say that I think we have an easy sailing in this race.

04:51.240 --> 04:54.760
I think we're going to win but it's going to be a tough contest.

04:54.760 --> 04:59.040
Our situation in Franklin is not as good today as it was six months ago.

04:59.040 --> 05:06.680
But I don't understand though, is why you think that Nixon's opposition will unite the Democratic

05:06.680 --> 05:07.920
Party.

05:07.920 --> 05:12.960
What is it that he has done as far as the rank and file of voters are concerned and independent

05:12.960 --> 05:15.720
voters except the mean to Democrats?

05:15.720 --> 05:21.280
Well, that's something of being mean to Democrats is something that will unite the Democrats.

05:21.280 --> 05:26.360
But I think you go back of course it's been a long history and I don't think it's worthwhile

05:26.360 --> 05:29.480
or probably appropriate to review that long history.

05:29.480 --> 05:35.080
And Simon Mr. Dixon, Nixon's campaign, he's has some pretty harsh words over the United

05:35.080 --> 05:42.000
States to say about Democrats in many various states and the Democratic rank and file and

05:42.000 --> 05:43.720
leaders haven't forgotten.

05:43.720 --> 05:47.520
Senator Keefe, former President Truman has had some pretty strong things to say about Republicans

05:47.520 --> 05:48.520
over the years too.

05:48.520 --> 05:49.520
Yes, he has, Mr. President.

05:49.520 --> 05:52.440
Well, why is it that this is something I've never been able to understand?

05:52.440 --> 05:57.360
Why it is that Democrats get so upset over things that Nixon says about them but they don't

05:57.360 --> 05:59.560
get upset over the things that they say about Republicans.

05:59.560 --> 06:01.800
Well, it's all just political give and take.

06:01.800 --> 06:03.920
Well, Mr. Truman, of course, have had our difference.

06:03.920 --> 06:08.560
I think in his big decisions he's been a great and good leader and I think he's growing

06:08.560 --> 06:11.840
in statute but he's not a candidate of either part of the president.

06:11.840 --> 06:14.640
No, but when he was a candidate he certainly had some strong things to say too.

06:14.640 --> 06:17.920
I can recall some comments about the 80th Congress he made to a pretty strong.

06:17.920 --> 06:19.520
But he didn't put it on a personal basis.

06:19.520 --> 06:24.880
Senator, you yourself had some strong things to say about some Democratic candidates at

06:24.880 --> 06:26.480
various times haven't you?

06:26.480 --> 06:29.400
I've usually expressed myself pretty freely, Mr. Raw.

06:29.400 --> 06:31.600
I can't remember exactly what you were talking about.

06:31.600 --> 06:33.400
Oh, we're quite aware there.

06:33.400 --> 06:37.880
And just a moment ago you made what I thought was very strong statement about your old

06:37.880 --> 06:40.920
neighbor and Richard Nixon only, you two used to live close together.

06:40.920 --> 06:41.920
You're saying it?

06:41.920 --> 06:42.920
I'm very fond of him.

06:42.920 --> 06:43.920
I mean, it's fine.

06:43.920 --> 06:47.680
Are you saying that you would not trust him with such important decisions as perhaps

06:47.680 --> 06:50.480
the decision whether or not to start a nuclear war?

06:50.480 --> 06:59.000
I say we're in a situation where in a little accident, both sides are armed with teeth,

06:59.000 --> 07:04.640
any accident, some misinformation might have set this war off.

07:04.640 --> 07:06.080
And I don't mean that I wouldn't trust him.

07:06.080 --> 07:10.240
I just don't think he has mature judgment as I would like to see in the White House.

07:10.240 --> 07:13.920
Well, by that, don't you imply that you wouldn't trust him with these decisions that

07:13.920 --> 07:16.120
may be in the fate of the world or the fate of the issues?

07:16.120 --> 07:18.600
I'd rather trust someone else with more experience.

07:18.600 --> 07:19.600
Other trust will move.

07:19.600 --> 07:20.600
Yes, naturally.

07:20.600 --> 07:24.040
Senator, you indicated a moment ago if I understood you correctly that the democratic situation

07:24.040 --> 07:26.040
was worse than it was six months ago.

07:26.040 --> 07:27.040
To what do you want to do?

07:27.040 --> 07:32.440
Well, I'll say frankly that I think Mr. Eisenhower has done a good job on his trip around

07:32.440 --> 07:33.440
the world.

07:33.440 --> 07:36.720
He's created a good impression, although that's different.

07:36.720 --> 07:42.000
That doesn't mean that the policies have been changed necessarily, but he's captured the

07:42.000 --> 07:47.360
imagination of the people, and that's given some strength to the Republican cause and

07:47.360 --> 07:48.360
not opinion.

07:48.360 --> 07:55.200
And I want to say that I admire and appreciate the president for his very grueling trip.

07:55.200 --> 07:56.600
I think he's done a whole lot.

07:56.600 --> 08:01.200
He's brought a lot of goodwill, and I think he's contributed something toward the possibility

08:01.200 --> 08:02.520
of having peace in the world.

08:02.520 --> 08:05.440
Well, Senator, obviously, you can't be against peace in the world.

08:05.440 --> 08:07.760
And I'm wondering what the issues will be then.

08:07.760 --> 08:10.560
What are you going to carry your democratic campaign on?

08:10.560 --> 08:13.480
Well, we'll have the issues of peace.

08:13.480 --> 08:18.400
We'll have the issues of what our defense structure is going to be.

08:18.400 --> 08:20.200
We'll have issues of interest rates.

08:20.200 --> 08:26.120
We'll have the issue of foreign program, housing program, many, many domestic issues.

08:26.120 --> 08:32.240
Whether we're going to develop our country, or whether we're going to call a halt to

08:32.240 --> 08:36.680
building of hydroelectric facilities and building up the richness of our country, things

08:36.680 --> 08:37.680
of that sort.

08:37.680 --> 08:39.040
We'll have a lot of issues.

08:39.040 --> 08:46.000
I've just been reading the advisory council's program, and so that we've got so many issues.

08:46.000 --> 08:53.600
Senator, on the basis of those issues, which is the current Democratic hopeful who best

08:53.600 --> 08:55.600
to remit you or your kind?

08:55.600 --> 09:00.560
I'm not in position to say, because all of our democratic hopefuls say at the present

09:00.560 --> 09:02.040
time that they're not candidates.

09:02.040 --> 09:04.880
I mean, they haven't announced their candidacy.

09:04.880 --> 09:07.320
I want to see how they're going to run into primaries.

09:07.320 --> 09:11.520
I want to hear what they're going to say about public issues.

09:11.520 --> 09:17.960
They're a fine group of people, but before I make any statement, if I ever do make a statement

09:17.960 --> 09:22.520
about which one I'm going to be for, a lot of things I want to see.

09:22.520 --> 09:26.280
I imagine the primaries will eliminate some of these democratic hopefuls.

09:26.280 --> 09:31.120
So now which one do you think is ahead?

09:31.120 --> 09:34.880
I'd rather not be put to that question.

09:34.880 --> 09:38.720
I think it's a very difficult question to answer.

09:38.720 --> 09:43.160
Senator Long, at the same line, though, they posed for whatever they were in their

09:43.160 --> 09:44.960
suspect in many quarters.

09:44.960 --> 09:48.840
Polls, though, show that similar to candidate today is running ahead.

09:48.840 --> 09:53.160
But even though you are a declared non-candidate, you said that you're not running for anything

09:53.160 --> 09:55.160
but re-electing it.

09:55.160 --> 09:56.160
Senator, I'm telling you something.

09:56.160 --> 09:59.560
I want to make that a must, but I want to be in Tennessee.

09:59.560 --> 10:06.640
I don't blame you, but the fact is that even though you've been more or less out of the

10:06.640 --> 10:13.160
national contention seen for four years, that you are still running third among the democratic

10:13.160 --> 10:15.680
possibilities of the people in some of the polls.

10:15.680 --> 10:17.080
I appreciate that fact.

10:17.080 --> 10:20.600
I've been trying to get myself out of the national picture and Dr. Gallup puts me back

10:20.600 --> 10:22.800
in there, never so often.

10:22.800 --> 10:29.320
But the fact of the case is Mr. Duffy, the 1952 I campaigned in every nook and corner

10:29.320 --> 10:30.320
of the United States.

10:30.320 --> 10:31.320
I met a lot of people.

10:31.320 --> 10:37.320
I did the same thing in 1956 so that I just know a lot of people in the country.

10:37.320 --> 10:42.560
I appreciate their friendship and I appreciate the fact that many of them have expressed

10:42.560 --> 10:44.800
a favorable interest in me.

10:44.800 --> 10:50.840
But in spite of that interest, as much as I appreciated, I'm not in the national picture.

10:50.840 --> 10:54.160
Senator, when Dr. Gallup puts you back in the national picture, do you consider that a

10:54.160 --> 10:55.160
friendly act?

10:55.160 --> 10:57.360
Well, that's a flattering act.

10:57.360 --> 11:03.660
Senator, a moment ago when you were outlining what the issues of the campaign might be,

11:03.660 --> 11:06.200
you didn't mention the issue of civil rights.

11:06.200 --> 11:11.080
Does the fact that you are not a national candidate now, but are running for the Senate from

11:11.080 --> 11:14.400
a Southern state, have anything to do with it?

11:14.400 --> 11:16.440
I didn't intend to admit it.

11:16.440 --> 11:21.040
I don't know exactly how the different democratic and the Republican Party will stand on that

11:21.040 --> 11:22.040
particular issue.

11:22.040 --> 11:27.760
As far as I'm concerned, I'm all in favor of doing everything we can to secure the right

11:27.760 --> 11:34.120
of people to vote and try to be thoughtful of the rights of all of our people, regardless

11:34.120 --> 11:36.120
of rates or religion.

11:36.120 --> 11:37.120
On a federal level?

11:37.120 --> 11:38.640
Yes, on a federal level.

11:38.640 --> 11:42.680
And I vote side each issue as it comes up.

11:42.680 --> 11:45.960
We do have, and I voted for the extension of the civil rights commission.

11:45.960 --> 11:50.600
It may be that on some issues, we ought to wait and see what they recommend, see what

11:50.600 --> 11:53.960
the findings they have, maybe we don't have enough information.

11:53.960 --> 11:59.000
I think an impunity of legislation against the South that make matters worse than they already

11:59.000 --> 12:01.440
are, have been doing the good.

