Unless an unexpected settlement should develop between labor and management on the steel

12:05.820 --> 12:09.960
front, it looks like this is going to be a major issue before the Congress when it comes

12:09.960 --> 12:11.120
back.

12:11.120 --> 12:15.160
If no agreement is reached, do you think that Congress will pass some remedial legislation?

12:15.160 --> 12:21.840
On-prem, that's a very distressing situation, this steel strike, and I think the 80 days

12:21.840 --> 12:24.880
expires about January 20th.

12:24.880 --> 12:29.560
Certainly Congress will have to do something about it if the strike continues on.

12:29.560 --> 12:33.320
I just what we'll be able to do will not be satisfactory to anybody.

12:33.320 --> 12:38.400
None of us will like labor courts, none of us like compulsory arbitration, and yet we can

12:38.400 --> 12:41.480
afford to see the economy of the country ground to a halt.

12:42.200 --> 12:47.360
Senator Smathers, I believe, suggested some kind of labor court.

12:47.360 --> 12:52.360
Whatever's done, I hope will be in a temporary basis and only a prior to those industries

12:52.360 --> 12:54.680
vested with a public interest.

12:54.680 --> 12:55.680
So do you, Senator?

12:55.680 --> 13:01.160
I hope in that connection also that the viewpoint of the consumer will be considered.

13:01.160 --> 13:05.720
We've had an increase in productivity and the steel industry between three and four percent

13:05.720 --> 13:08.040
for the last few years.

13:08.040 --> 13:13.280
That increase has been divided between industry and labor without the consumer getting much

13:13.280 --> 13:16.480
benefit in the way of reduced prices.

13:16.480 --> 13:21.200
I want somebody, if we're going to have some method of settlement or some formula to consider

13:21.200 --> 13:24.160
the consumer, the purchaser of steel also.

13:24.160 --> 13:28.360
Doesn't that get you into price fixing on a government level?

13:28.360 --> 13:35.160
Well, I don't like price fixing, but of course, if we're not going to have statesmanship

13:35.160 --> 13:40.560
and consideration on the part of industry and labor to get this strike over with, we're

13:40.560 --> 13:44.360
going to have to do something about it, but the solution will be, I don't know.

13:44.360 --> 13:49.000
No, but you feel that if labor and management can't get together on this, with an equitable

13:49.000 --> 13:51.960
relationship to the consumer, that the government will have to get in.

13:51.960 --> 13:57.800
They're going to have to do something because our defense effort, our rockets, missiles,

13:57.800 --> 14:02.400
guns, planes, everything that we're doing depends upon having steel.

14:02.400 --> 14:04.640
